						Chymicis:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						in Politicis, aut Pragmaticis: in Polemicis[,]
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						aut stratagematicis: in mundi deniq[ue] potentissimis arcanis, 
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						aut Neopracticis; qua[e] Sunt De profundi[s]
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						eruta, fortissim&eacute;q[ue] multiplicata. Omnes 
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						excutit excellentissimos Locos Commu[nes]
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						et Sola decerpit suo Scopo maxim&egrave; Conducentia. 
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ociosis tam professoribus, qu&agrave;m scholasticis 
						infinitas tot Auctorum nugas relinquit.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Eutrapelus is always serious and entirely adamantine in his most worthy studies:
				in Mathematics, or in Chemistry; in Politics, or in Pragmatic activities; in Wars or in Strategies;
				and finally, in the most powerful things of the world, hidden or neopractical, which were plucked from
				the depths and most boldly multiplied. 
				He shakes the most excellent common places and gathers only those which lead most to his goal.
				With the unemployed or with professors (as with scholars), he leaves behind the infinite trifles
				of all authors.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
